{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1ab601f-0afb-4a7e-b3f8-b5193bfa3be9","content":"## The Problem\n\n.NET MAUI's Android workload **bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17**. When your `JAVA_HOME` points to an external JDK (Temurin), the build picks it up instead of the bundled one, which can cause compatibility issues with the Android build tooling.\n\n## The Fix\n\n**Option 1 — Unset `JAVA_HOME` for the build** (quickest):\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Point to the bundled JDK permanently** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(ANDROID_SDK_HOME)/jdk/microsoft_dist_openjdk_17</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr find the exact bundled path with:\n\n```bash\nls ~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/\n# or\ndotnet android sdk info\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Scope `JAVA_HOME`** so it only affects non-MAUI work by removing it from your shell profile (`~/.zshrc`) and setting it only when needed.\n\n**Recommendation:** Option 1 to verify this is the issue, then Option 3 for a permanent solution. Let .NET MAUI manage its own JDK.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"11e76e1c-389a-42b4-acae-ab4250061870","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThe common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java is that .NET MAUI / Xamarin.Android requires a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI requires JDK 17, but there can be issues with certain JDK distributions or versions.\n\nActually, the most common issue is that .NET MAUI Android builds require the **Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution specifically, or at least a JDK that's compatible. But more specifically, the issue is usually about the JDK version compatibility.\n \nI should consider that .NET MAUI typically bundles its own JDK through the Android workload, so the build system might not be picking up the user's JAVA_HOME environment variable at all. Even though they have JDK 17 installed, which matches the requirement for .NET 8, the issue could be that the bundled JDK isn't properly configured or there's a path resolution problem on their system. The Android build tools have specific JDK requirements, and the most likely culprit is a conflict between .NET's bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and the user's JAVA_HOME pointing to Temurin—the fix usually involves either unsetting JAVA_HOME to let .NET use its bundled version, or ensuring both are compatible. Unset `JAVA_HOME` and let .NET use its bundled JDK, or point `JAVA_HOME` to the Microsoft OpenJDK that .NET installs (typically at `~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_openjdk_17.x.x` on macOS or via the .NET workload path).\n\nWithout knowing the exact error, the most likely culprit is that .NET MAUI's Android SDK expects its own bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and an external Temurin JDK can interfere. The solution is either unsetting `JAVA_HOME` entirely, setting `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the .csproj to the correct JDK, or ensuring the Microsoft OpenJDK from the Android workload is being used.","outputTokens":1618},"id":"c7bb525d-757b-4559-aec5-177fbfd99bfe","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:50:42.317Z","parentId":"419cd588-8e37-43e5-9c9b-7ba0a4e7351b"}
